}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 2-3.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Virgil's 'Scholastic' credentials seem strong.  See Giuseppe Tarozzi's appreciation (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Il \softline
canto XVIII del "Purgatorio"}{\plain \fs24 \f1  ["Lectura Dantis Orsanmichele"] [Florence: Sansoni, 1901]}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ), p. 7: \softline
Virgil 'here represents the idealized figure of the medieval docent.'  A close analysis of his \softline
discourse in the preceding canto, such as may be found, in English, in Singleton's commentary, \softline
reveals a line of argument that is closely based on Thomistic texts.  In keeping with such discourse \softline
and for the first time since }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XVI.48, Virgil is saluted by his pupil as 'professor' (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 dottore}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ).  \softline
For the other terms used to describe Virgil's role as guide in the poem, see the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
II.140.  (Virgil is referred to as }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 dottore}{\plain \fs24 \f1  elsewhere as follows: }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf. }{\plain \fs24 \f1  V.70, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf. }{\plain \fs24 \f1  V.123, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf. }{\plain \fs24 \f1  XVI.13, \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf. }{\plain \fs24 \f1  XVI.48, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXI.22, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXI.131, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXIV.14).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab In fact, Virgil has rarely been referred to or addressed by Dante with such fervent \softline
admiration as here and shortly later in this canto, when he will be 'padre verace' (true father  --  7), \softline
'Maestro' (Master -- 10), and then 'father' again (13).  See the note to vv. 17-18.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 4.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   In this and the next canto the protagonist's forward movement in understanding is \softline
underlined by the adjective }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 nuovo}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (new): used here for his new 'thirst,' at verse 141 for his 'new \softline
thought' in reaction to the departure of the penitents in Sloth, and at }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XIX.56, in his \softline
reference to the new dream he has just had on this terrace.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \ul0 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 8.}{\plain \fs24 \f1    Dante's 'timid wish' should probably be considered related to intellectual sloth (see \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XVII.130, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 lento amore}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [laggard love]).  How could Dante have considered himself 'timid' \softline
in seeking the truth?  Had he involved himself in a less than urgent affection for the good, the \softline
charge would seem appropriate.  Since it is the author who makes the charge, it might seem that \softline
he himself believed that he did not always display the zeal necessary for loving well.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 13-15.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Why, one might ask, after Virgil's long speech in the last canto, should Dante want \softline
Virgil to 'expound' love when he seems just now to have finished (with suitable fanfare) doing 
precisely that?  What the protagonist means is 'expatiate upon,' 'explain more precisely,' the \softline
argument just now presented.  The word }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 dimostrare}{\plain \fs24 \f1  is here, in fact, a verb based on the Latin \softline
noun }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 demonstratio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , as used to refer to the development of proofs by means of syllogistic \softline
demonstration.  See }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Paradiso}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXIV.96.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 17-18.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Virgil's words reflect Matthew 15:14, where Jesus says that the Pharisees are blind \softline
guides of the blind who follow them, adding that guide and flock shall all end up falling into a \softline
ditch.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab In }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  I.xi.4 Dante cites this passage, directing its barb against 'those wicked Italians \softline
who praise the vernacular of others while disparaging their own' (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Conv}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . I.xi.1) and who are \softline
therefore likewise headed toward disaster.  As Francesco Mazzoni argues ("Latini, Brunetto" \softline
[ED.1971.3], p. 580b), in this connection it is difficult not to think of Dante's fellow Florentine \softline
Brunetto Latini, who wrote his encyclopedic }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Tresor}{\plain \fs24 \f1  in French rather than in his native vernacular \softline
(see Andr{\f2\u233\'e9}}{\plain \fs24 \f1  P{\f2\u233\'e9}zard [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante sous la pluie de feu}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (Paris: Vrin, 1950)}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ] for extensive development of \softline
this idea).  Also to be considered are the words, written shortly before or shortly after this passage \softline
(on the problems of dating }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dve}{\plain \fs24 \f1  and }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Conv.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  see Hollander [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante: A Life in Works}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (New Haven: \softline
Yale University Press, 2001)}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ], pp. 54-55), in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 De vulgari eloquentia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  I.xiii.1, when Dante 'exiles' \softline
Brunetto from the illustrious and courtly vernacular that he is championing, relegating him to the \softline
ash heap of the municipal vernacular, the 'street talk' that is to be avoided by serious poets.  In \softline
what seems to have been a change of heart, Brunetto, in the fifteenth canto of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , will be \softline
treated generously as Dante's vernacular 'teacher' (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf. }{\plain \fs24 \f1  XV.85), just as Virgil was his first Latin \softline
guide.  It seems clear that these two are joined only by Guido Guinizzelli as explicitly paternal \softline
figures of writerly authority for the Tuscan poet.\par
