}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 19-21.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Virgil, responding to Dante's request, carries his analysis of the loving human mind \softline
to the next level, the role of the rational soul in determining human choice and, therefore, action.  \softline
This tercet establishes the subject of Virgil's difficult clarification (vv. 22-39): how mind (the \softline
rational soul, created directly by God and instilled in the embryo last [see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXV.67-75]) \softline
reacts appetitively to external things.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 22-27.}{\plain \fs24 \f1    The }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 apprensiva}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (power of perception), already implicitly referred to in Dante's \softline
apostrophe of the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 imaginativa}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (faculty of imagination) in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XVII.13-15, is the faculty of \softline
perception that reacts to the capturing of an image (referred to here as an }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 intenzione}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ) of external \softline
reality in the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 imaginazione}{\plain \fs24 \f1  or }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 fantasia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (see the note to verse 13-18).  The mind, as opposed to the \softline
'natural desire' of the senses (see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XVII.93 for this distinction), which is always errorless, is \softline
responsible for its choices and may err.  If its perception inclines toward what it contemplates, \softline
that is what we call love.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab For a discussion of this passage in light of the Aristotelian and Arabic roots of Dante's \softline
word }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 intenzione}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , see the entry for that term by Tullio Gregory (ED.1971.3), pp. 480b-481b.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 28-33.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Desire, love in action, now continues by extending toward its goal and remaining \softline
in this state as long as it takes pleasure in its appetition.  (For fire as an example of 'natural desire,' \softline
see the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XVII.91-92.)  Thus here Dante is comparing intellectual desire to natural \softline
desire, but also insisting on the distance between them.  Natural desire can never be culpable (e.g., \softline
fire always 'desires' to rise -- that is its natural inclination).  There is perhaps no moment in the \softline
poem of greater danger to its essential philosophical position.  Is human desire -- for money, food, \softline
or sexual pleasure -- not as 'natural' as this?  Does anyone }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 not}{\plain \fs24 \f1  desire these things?  Dante's \softline
attempt to persuade us, as he may well have realized, reflects that of another }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 dottore}{\plain \fs24 \f1  and }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 maestro}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , \softline
Jesus.  He, as the Gospels amply testify, also spoke frequently, in his parables, in terms of human \softline
desires that all could understand, e.g., of money, agriculture, marriage.  In all cases the listener is \softline
encouraged, even impelled, to understand that such pleasures, as great as they may be, will seem \softline
as nothing compared to the joys of Heaven.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Padoan ({\u8220\'93}}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  Canto XVIII,{\u8221\'94} in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lectura Dantis Scaligera}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Florence: Le Monnier, \softline
1967 (1964}{\plain \fs24 \f1 )]), pp. 668-70, suggests that Dante's definition of love in this canto intrinsically \softline
corrects Francesca's claims for the ineluctable nature of passionate love (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . V.103).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Dante was surely right to let his language here reflect an essentially sexual view of love.  \softline
Consider the last verse of this part of the passage, 'fin che la cosa amata il fa gioire' (as long as it \softline
enjoys the thing it loves [for this understanding of the conjunction }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 fin che}{\plain \fs24 \f1  see Francesco Mazzoni, \softline
cited by Bosco/Reggio in their commentary on this passage; in opposition, reading 'until it attains \softline
the thing it loves' as being more Thomistic, see Alfred A. Triolo (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XVIII," in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante's \softline
"Divine Comedy," Introductory Readings II: "Purgatorio,"}{\plain \fs24 \f1  ed. Tibor Wlassics [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lectura Dantis \softline
(virginiana)}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , 12, supplement, Charlottesville: University of Virginia, 1993]}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ), p. 268]).  Arriving at \softline
this point in the argument, a reader would have to be pardoned for believing that whatever good \softline
the spirit of love pursues is }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 ipso facto}{\plain \fs24 \f1  good, just as the protagonist himself will shortly seem to \softline
believe (vv. 43-45).  But what is the nature of the 'moto spiritale' (movement of the spirit) of the 
'captive mind'?  That question is reflected in the crucial and concluding portion of Virgil's \softline
discourse.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 34-39.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The main candidates for this unenviable denomination, the errant folk who believe \softline
that }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 all}{\plain \fs24 \f1  love is good (a proposition, as we have seen, that we might have considered unassailable a \softline
moment ago), have been Epicureans.  In the modern period this view is first offered by Scartazzini \softline
(comm. to verse 35) but then is held by many twentieth-century commentators.  Grabher (comm. \softline
to vv. 19-39) is of the opinion that this is the position of all love poets, including the younger \softline
Dante.  His view, sometimes combined with that of Scartazzini, has grown increasingly attractive \softline
to recent commentators.  Clearly, anyone who believes that love is in itself and always \softline
praiseworthy is among this group.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab The 'imprint' on the 'wax' of our love becomes the crucial symbolic expression of the \softline
concept developed here.  The 'wax' clearly refers to the innate human potential to love, which is \softline
'stamped' by the image that the mind has extracted from reality; that 'stamp' may either be worthy \softline
or unworthy, while the 'wax' is always worthy.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 40-45.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   It is, despite Virgil's last insistence on the (implicit) need for the proper exercise of \softline
the free will in choosing the objects of one's desire, understandable that Dante, up to this point, \softline
believes that the mind is completely responsive to internalized (by the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 apprensiva}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ) external stimuli \softline
(the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 intenzione}{\plain \fs24 \f1  -- see verse 23), and thus irreprehensible in whatever choice it makes.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 46-48.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   This passage offers perhaps the only apparently material evidence in the poem that \softline
would tie both Virgil and Beatrice to an allegorical status, his role being that of Reason, hers, \softline
Faith.  But see Hollander ("}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  II: The New Song and the Old," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lectura Dantis \softline
[virginiana]}{\plain \fs24 \f1  6 [1990]}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ), p. 42, n. 2: 'It is from Virgil's lips that we first hear the name Beatrice... in \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 : VI.46; XV.77; XVIII.48.  In her first three nominal presences in this }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cantica}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ... she is \softline
associated first with hope (VI.32), then with love (XV.68; XV.71; XV,74), then with faith.'  Thus \softline
associated with the three theological virtues, Beatrice can be seen as possessing all of them; she \softline
probably should not be seen as representing any one of them, or as having an 'allegorical' status in \softline
this poem.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab In keeping with all of the ratiocination found in this canto, words for 'reason' in various \softline
noun and verb forms are found in it far more than in any other (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXII finishes a distant \softline
second with four occurrences), as follows: vv. 1, 12, 46, 65, 67, 85, 120.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 49-75.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The three cantos at the center of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  devote what may seem immoderate \softline
space to what Benedetto Croce disliked in Dante, his 'non-poesia,' his 'structure,' his mere }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 allotria}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
(the 'extraneous matter' of philosophy or theology that Croce deprecated in Dante; opposing such \softline
views, Fernando Salsano [{\u8220\'93}}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  Canto XV,{\u8221\'94} in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lectura Dantis Scaligera}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (Florence: Le \softline
Monnier, 1967)}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ], p. 542, speaks of the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Comedy}{\plain \fs24 \f1  as 'un poema e non un libro di poesie'}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ).  For an \softline
examination of what Croce's kind of aestheticizing denies to Dante's poem, precisely the validity \softline
and beauty of its conceptual structure, see Giorgio Stabile ("Cosmologia e teologia nella \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Commedia}{\plain \fs24 \f1 : la caduta di Lucifero e il rovesciamento del mondo," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Letture classensi}{\plain \fs24 \f1  12 [1983]}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ), pp. \softline
139-44.  Stabile is surely correct in arguing that Croce's oppositional binome structure/poetry fails \softline
to account for the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 aesthetic}{\plain \fs24 \f1  possibilities of Dante's versified conceptual thinking.  Marco's long \softline
speech in XVI (65-129), Virgil's in XVII (91-139), and Virgil's concluding two in this canto (16-39; 49-75) should be looked upon, as should the related discursive portions of Cantos XXIV and \softline
XXV, as part of a continuing development of a complex statement about the nature and function \softline
of love, presented from different vantage points.  In Canto XXIV, Dante's presentation of the \softline
Holy Spirit's creative role in helping to make the writings of a handful of poets acceptable to God \softline
prepares for the following treatment in Canto XXV of the way the Holy Spirit is breathed into all \softline
of us, thus explaining how eventually a very few of us may become acceptable to God as His \softline
saints in paradise.  In these three cantos Marco the Lombard explains the need for proper civil \softline
governance because our free will may elsewise lead us astray, while Virgil takes up a related \softline
topic, the need for us individually to use our free will correctly in choosing and responding to the \softline
objects of our attention and affection.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 49-60.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The only 'substantial form' to be both distinct from matter and joined to it is the \softline
human soul, which is formed by pure divine intellect (as are the angels) and by emotional and \softline
vegetative powers (as are the beasts).  Its }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 specifica vertute}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (defining disposition), as we learn at \softline
vv. 55-57, is composed of primal intellect and primal will, and is only perceptible in the action of \softline
the soul, not in itself.  Now, leaving intellection out of consideration, Virgil continues: We have \softline
no recollection or current understanding of our original inclination (to love God), yet we do \softline
demonstrate its presence in us, as the eagerness of bees for making honey reveals their 'defining \softline
disposition.'  This kind of (natural) will exists beyond and before moral assent.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 61-66.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   This innate will (see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXI.105, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 la virt{\f3 \'6a} che vuole}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [the power that wills]) \softline
must accord with }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 la virt{\f3 \'6a} che consiglia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  ('the faculty that counsels'), the higher intellect that should \softline
