}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 67-69.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Aristotle's }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Ethics}{\plain \fs24 \f1  is probably Dante's main source for his views on morality (a view \softline
supported by Benvenuto da Imola [comm. to vv. 67-75]).  However, to account for the plurality \softline
of the reference, Poletto (comm. to these verses) sensibly refers to Dante's own earlier phrasing \softline
(found in the words of his guide, Virgil), 'I speak of Aristotle and of Plato / and of many others' \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . III.43-44).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 70-75.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Virgil's lengthy discourse concludes with his final insistence on the pivotal role of \softline
free will in individual moral responsibility and looks forward (as Benvenuto was perhaps the first \softline
to realize [see his comm. to vv. 67-75]) to Beatrice's remarks on the subject in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Paradiso}{\plain \fs24 \f1  V.19-24, \softline
asseverating that the freedom of the will is the greatest of God's gifts to humankind.  Many of the \softline
early commentators find this a convenient place for them to reassert the 'allegorical' valence of \softline
Beatrice, here interpreted as 'Theology.'  In the past 150 years most commentators are content to \softline
leave the allegorical equation in abeyance, merely referring to Beatrice as herself.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 76-81.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Returning to narrative, the poet returns to telling the time.  The moon, as the \softline
slowest 'planet' in Dante's astronomy, is fittingly the celestial body referred to on the terrace of \softline
Sloth.  Its appearance is compared by Benvenuto (comm. to these lines) to the semicircular fire in \softline
a lighthouse, glowing throughout the night.  Commentators are divided as to exactly what is \softline
involved here, i.e., whether it is the moon's rising that is referred to or its current position in the \softline
sky.  Singleton's discussion (comm. to vv. 76-78) resuscitates Edward Moore's early essay (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 The 
