p. 688n., agrees.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 87-88.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Again a detail -- Dante's somnolence -- establishes a connection with Sloth.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 89-90.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   These penitents, as opposed to the wrathful, move in the same counterclockwise \softline
direction that is followed by Dante and Virgil.  It would seem that, while the movement of Dante \softline
to the right is morally determined, that of the penitents is not, is rather the result of aesthetic \softline
considerations.  Review of the various groups that are in motion suggests that such is the case. \softline
Below the gate, we see that the excommunicate are moving rightwards (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . III.59), while the \softline
late-repentant seem to be heading to the left (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . V.23).  On the terraces, the prideful seem to \softline
be moving right (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . X.100), while the wrathful are headed left (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XV.142).  Here in Sloth \softline
the penitents come from behind Virgil and Dante but are moving in the same direction (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . \softline
XVIII.90).  Farther up the mountain the penitent gluttons are also moving counterclockwise \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXIII.19-20), while the two distinct bands of the lustful proceed in two different \softline
directions (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXVI.29).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 91-96.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   This is a fairly rare occurrence in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , a simile based explicitly on classical \softline
materials (but see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . IX.34-42, for the similetic reference to Statius's Achilles).  And there will \softline
not be another (now based on a passage in Lucan) until }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXIV.64-69.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Ismenus and Asopus are names of rivers, the first flowing through the city of Thebes, the \softline
second near it.  Beginning with Jacopo della Lana (comm. to these verses), commentators have \softline
offered the opinion, from time to time, that Dante's source here is Statius (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Thebaid}{\plain \fs24 \f1  IX).  Ismenos \softline
is named at IX.404, his 'brother' Asopos at IX.449.  That passage includes two references to the \softline
orgiastic Bacchic rites (IX.434-436; 478-480) to which Dante here refers.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 97-98.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Running in a group to counteract the painful memory of their solitary slothful \softline
behaviors on earth, all these gathered penitents may put contemporary readers in mind of the \softline
massed crowds of runners in metropolitan marathons.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 99-138.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   With the exception of the concluding interaction with the angel in the following \softline
canto, separated by Dante's sleep and dream from the action on the fourth terrace, all the usual \softline
'events' of any terrace are here condensed -- in the compressed style appropriate to the description 
of the newly zealous -- into these forty verses.  All terraces include the following features in the \softline
same order: (1) description of the physical aspect of the terrace, (2) exemplars of the countering \softline
virtue, (3) description of the penitents, (4) recitation of their sins by particular penitents, (5) \softline
exemplars of the vice, (6) appearance to Dante of the angel representing the opposing virtue.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab We might want to reflect on the extraordinary artisanship of the presentation of the \softline
exemplary material on the earlier terraces, things not matched by what we find in earlier medieval \softline
poems: the 'speaking' (and odoriferous) intaglios of Pride, the voices streaking overhead in Envy, \softline
the ecstatic visions of Wrath.  It is as though Dante had used up all the brilliant new techniques of \softline
presentation of which he could think and now, for the rest of the ascent, subsides to the perfectly \softline
acceptable artistic level of utterance, leaving us to marvel at what he had done before.  On three \softline
of the last four terraces the names (sometimes accompanied by reference to significant deeds) of \softline
all exemplary figures are simply called out by the penitents, while on the terrace of Gluttony, in a \softline
variant, the two trees do the talking.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 99-102.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Petrocchi's punctuation of this passage and of that devoted to the final exemplary \softline
figures, vv. 133-138, is probably not well conceived.  Since there are two voices speaking, and \softline
since each pair of examples is divided by the copulative 'e' (and), it seems nearly certain that each \softline
voice recites a single example.  Thus the 'e' in both passages should, alone, be outside quotation \softline
marks, thus marking each of the two statements as being registered by a different voice.  \softline
Otherwise, what use was there in having }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 two}{\plain \fs24 \f1  anonymous voices giving the examples?  Scartazzini \softline
(comm. to verse 99) points out that the first two speakers, by virtue of leading the pack, are \softline
intrinsically the 'fastest' and thus most qualified to offer the positive }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 exempla}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , while the last two, \softline
bringing up the rear, most appropriately give forth the negative ones.  See also Pier Giorgio Ricci \softline
("Il Canto XVIII del }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Nuove letture dantesche}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , vol. IV [Florence: Le Monnier, \softline
1970]}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ), pp. 260-63, discussing the paired voices and the problem with the punctuation adopted by \softline
Petrocchi.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Some of the earliest commentators believe that the reference is to the precipitous escape \softline
from Herod's decree and the flight of the holy family into Egypt (a misinterpretation that surfaced \softline
again in the Renaissance in the commentaries of Landino and Vellutello).  However, beginning \softline
with Pietro di Dante (Pietro1, comm. to verse 100) the obvious citation of Luke 1:39 has been \softline
recognized as governing this example.  Mary, having been told by Gabriel during the \softline
Annunciation of Elizabeth's miraculous pregnancy in her old age (which will result in the birth of \softline
John the Baptist), 'abiit in montana cum festinatione... et salutavit Elisabeth' (went with good \softline
speed into the hill country... and offered her salutation to Elizabeth).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 101-102.}{\plain \fs24 \f1    The Roman example paired with Mary is none other than Julius Caesar.  It is \softline
notable that in Lucan (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Phars}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . III.453) Caesar's rushing off to do battle in Spain is not the result of \softline
military strategy but of his being bored (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 inpatiens}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ) with the prolonged efforts to lay siege to \softline
Marseilles.  Further, his eventual victory at Lerida is described by Lucan as being the result of \softline
fortunate changes in the weather (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Phars}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . IV.48-49).  Thus Dante's praise of him here is clearly at \softline
odds with Lucan's (always) withering scorn for the Great Man whom he so desperately despises.  \softline
For the entire question of Dante's divided view of Julius Caesar, in one view the first, God-sent \softline
emperor of Rome, in another the destroyer of the Republic and of Roman virtue, see Stull and \softline
Hollander ("The Lucanian Source of Dante's Ulysses," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Studi Danteschi}{\plain \fs24 \f1  63 [1991 (1997)]}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ), pp. \softline
33-43.  This is one of Julius's few positive moments in Dante's poem; and Dante needed to 
disregard Lucan's views in order to present him favorably.  John of Serravalle's gloss (to vv. 97-102) might have pleased him: 'Cesar fuit recte inimicus accidie, fuit valde sollicitus.  Semper \softline
dicebat militibus: Venite; nunquam dixit: Ite' (Caesar was indeed an enemy to sloth, a \softline
pronouncedly zealous one at that.  He was always calling to his soldiers 'Come' and never once \softline
said 'Go').  For Dante's previous and next far less favorable references to Julius, see the notes to \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  IX.133-138 and XXVI.76-78.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 103.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   On every other terrace the penitents have a prayer that they speak in common when \softline
they are not interrupted by other forms of observance or by conversation with Dante and Virgil \softline
(see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XI.1-24; XIII.50-51; XVI.19; XIX.73; XXIII.11; XXV.121).  The terrace of Sloth \softline
offers the only exception, as though the previous }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 acedia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  of these penitents took from them the \softline
privilege of Christian prayer.  The gloss of Carroll (to vv. 103-105) is interesting: 'The idea \softline
seems... to be the danger of contemplation of good deeds, without an eager and immediate effort \softline
to imitate them.  Mere "study" of them may end in the "little love" which produces sloth.  It is \softline
only when "study" is accompanied by action that it "makes grace bud again.''  For Dante, a man \softline
devoted to the pursuit of the morally engaged active life, certain occasions for prayer perhaps \softline
appeared to offer a potential escape from one's civil and religious duty in the world.  Men and \softline
women of such disposition are thus, here in their penitence, denied the comfort of prayer until \softline
such time as prayer will be totally zealous, not the occasion for a moment of repose from worldly \softline
responsibility or, for that matter, from proper monastic exertion.  }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Acedia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  was frequently \softline
associated with improper monastic }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 otium}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , a withdrawal from the world but from one's duty to \softline
God, as well, surely a great temptation in the relative ease allowed by monastic life.'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 104-105.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The phrase 'per poco amor' (for lack of love) and the word 'studio' (the Italian \softline
equivalent of the Latin word for 'zeal') combine to underline the defining vice and virtue of this \softline
terrace.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
