}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 118-120.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   San Zeno, just outside the city of Verona (and, by common consent, one of the \softline
most beautiful churches in Italy), was also the site of a monastery.  Its nameless abbot, who \softline
speaks here, is generally identified as Gherardo II, who served, during the reign of the Emperor \softline
Frederick I, from 1163 until his death in 1187.  Frederick Barbarossa, emperor (from 1152 until \softline
his death in 1190) as Frederick I, was a grandfather of Frederick II (emperor 1215-1250).  \softline
Dante's overall opinion of him is difficult to measure, since he so rarely refers to him, but in the \softline
two passages that do invoke his presence, here and in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Epistle}{\plain \fs24 \f1  VI.20, his destruction of Milan in \softline
1162 for its anti-imperial activities is clearly applauded.  On the question of Dante's views of \softline
Barbarossa see Bruno Nardi ("Dante e il buon Barbarossa," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 L'Alighieri}{\plain \fs24 \f1  7 [1966], pp. 3-27}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ).\par
