here to be taken ironically, see Tommaseo's commentary to this passage.  One may add that the \softline
thirty occasions in the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Commedia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  on which a reader finds the epithet combined with a name or 
title (e.g., 'buon Marzucco,' 'buon maestro') do not reveal a single one in which an ironic reading \softline
seems warranted.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 121-126.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Dante, welcomed by the Scaligeri family to Verona in 1303-4, there enjoyed the \softline
first happy time of his exile.  His memories of those rulers of the city give rise to a }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 post-eventum}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
prophecy.  Alberto della Scala was lord of Verona until his death in 1301, by which time he had \softline
appointed his lame, illegitimate son, Giuseppe (1263-1313), to serve as abbot of the monastery (in \softline
1292), for the rest of his days.  Alberto was succeeded by his eldest legitimate son, Bartolommeo, \softline
nearly certainly Dante's first host in Verona.  Upon Bartolommeo's death, in 1304, Alberto's \softline
second son, Alboino, became lord (many believe that Dante and Alboino did not get along, thus \softline
explaining Dante's departure from Verona ca. 1304), a position he held until his death in 1311, \softline
when he was succeeded by Cangrande della Scala, the third legitimate son and Dante's patron and \softline
host when the poet returned to Verona ca. 1314.\par
